    "body": "# Journal \u2014 Monday, 25 May 2026\n\n> [!info] First entry\n> The first PF framework journal. Goals for this practice: complete it (build the habit) and refine the process as it surfaces friction. Refinement notes captured in [[Library/processes/pf-journal]] as we went.\n\n## Recovery (Garmin, last night)\n\n- Sleep score: **79** (FAIR), total **7h 17m** (deep 49m / REM 94m / light 294m / awake 15m)\n- HRV last-night avg: **45** (weekly 46, **BALANCED**)\n- Body battery: **+40 charged / \u221228 drained** \u2014 net positive\n- Training readiness: **61** (MODERATE; `MOD_RT_LOW_SS_MOD_STRESS_HISTORY_NEG`)\n- Resting HR 57, day stress avg 35\n\n**Reflection on these numbers:** Body's ok and the numbers say so \u2014 HRV balanced, swim was all Z1 base work, net energy positive on the day. The honest read is **tired but not physically tired** \u2014 the day's load was cognitive, not muscular. The Cowork session (5+ hours of substantive build / debug / consolidation) is what the body is feeling now, not the swim. Garmin actually picks an echo of it up via the `MOD_STRESS_HISTORY_NEG` flag and the low-sleep-score factor \u2014 the framework's interpretation of the day is correct, even if the labels are physical.\n\n## IPSATIVE goals\n\n- **Yesterday's micro-goal**: not set (first entry, no continuity)\n- **Tomorrow's micro-goal**: **get the morning run done first thing, before any other work begins.**\n  - **Why**: aligns with the W22 weekly plan (Wed bike is the leading indicator; tomorrow's run is the leading-indicator-of-the-leading-indicator). Defends against the historical \"I'll do it later\" pattern, where \"later\" gets eaten by a CD field-work pull that has no defined end time.\n  - **Clean Y/N tomorrow evening**: was the run logged in Garmin before 09:00?\n\n## Commitment Continuum \u2014 today's position\n\n**Maximum Compliant.**\n\nHad to work at it. Constantly reminded myself of the goals and the whys. It hasn't come natural \u2014 course-corrected a few times during the day. Doing the right things, but the \"why\" still has to be actively held in mind rather than running automatically. The Compliant \u2192 Committed transition is exactly about that gap closing.\n\nThe thing that lifts this above mid-Compliant: setting tomorrow's IPSATIVE goal a few hours ago is itself a **Compelled**-style move \u2014 choosing against my own future weakness (the leak-job afternoon, the whim, the diary lying about availability). So: Compliant on the day-as-lived, acting Compelled on the day-yet-to-come. The gap closing is the journey.\n\n## Ownership\n\n**Owned the day in general.**\n\nThe signature move today was deliberately moving the planned run to tomorrow. Wording from the Xhale note to Loren:\n\n> *\"Loren, I have moved this intentionally, this is a controlled and sensible move, not a move because I lost control of the day. I had left Tuesday free as we had a full day survey possibly in, and for some slippage, but now the survey is only half a day and on top of that its roasting here and I am tired so rather than get the run in today I think its more sensible to do it tomorrow.\"*\n\nThat's Compelled-style ownership in the day's behaviour: the day didn't eat the run \u2014 I moved it deliberately based on better information (Tuesday's survey halved, heat, accumulated fatigue), and I communicated the move to my coach in the moment. Not a retroactive justification \u2014 a real-time choice.\n\n**Externalised**: none of substance today.\n\n## Control the Controllables\n\n**None today.**\n\nNo energy spent on things outside my control. Nothing influenceable was let drift.\n\n## HF Matrix \u2014 today's position\n\n**Resilience** (top-left: positive thinking + negative emotion / fatigue).\n\nHad to work at it. The big difference *this week* \u2014 and this is the framing that lifted the whole answer \u2014 is **how much better I feel**. Setting the goals has given me something like a roadmap and a plan, something tangible to achieve and work towards, a sense of direction.\n\nStill takes willpower at this stage to stick to it and not fall back into the firefighting habits I've built up. That comes down to priorities: before jumping for something I'm automatically classifying as urgent and needing-doing-now, I check myself and ask \"is it really urgent, and does it justify sabotaging the day and the plan?\"\n\nThat check mechanism is the antidote to both the ADHD whim-tendency and the CD field-work pull. It's also what's keeping me in Resilience rather than slipping to Self-Sabotage or Low Functioning when the fatigue lands.\n\n## One lesson for tomorrow\n\n**Before reflexively jumping on something I'm calling urgent, pause and check \u2014 is it really urgent, and does it justify sabotaging the day and the plan? Direction comes from the plan, not the inbox.**"
  },
